JENKINS INSTALLATION & CONFIGURATION
Ubuntu (AWS EC2 â€“ t2.medium)
   sudo apt update -y
   sudo apt upgrade -y


STEP 2: INSTALL JAVA 17 (MANDATORY)
Jenkins requires Java. We standardize on Java 17 (LTS).
   sudo apt install openjdk-17-jdk -y


Verify:
  java -version


STEP 3: ADD JENKINS OFFICIAL REPOSITORY (SECURE METHOD)
Add Jenkins signing key:
   curl -fsSL https://pkg.jenkins.io/debian-stable/jenkins.io-2023.key | sudo tee \
/usr/share/keyrings/jenkins-keyring.asc > /dev/null


Add Jenkins repository
   echo deb [signed-by=/usr/share/keyrings/jenkins-keyring.asc] \
https://pkg.jenkins.io/debian-stable binary/ | sudo tee \
/etc/apt/sources.list.d/jenkins.list > /dev/null


STEP 4: INSTALL JENKINS
    sudo apt update -y
    sudo apt install jenkins -y


STEP 5: START & ENABLE JENKINS
    sudo systemctl start jenkins
    sudo systemctl enable jenkins


Check status:
   sudo systemctl status jenkins


You must see:
Active: active (running)


STEP 6: OPEN PORT 8080 IN AWS (CRITICAL)
In the EC2 Security Group attached to this instance:
Add an inbound rule:
Type: Custom TCP
Port: 8080
Source: 0.0.0.0/0 (training only)

Save rules.



STEP 7: ACCESS JENKINS FROM BROWSER

Open in your browser:

http://<EC2_PUBLIC_IP>:8080



STEP 8: GET INITIAL ADMIN PASSWORD
On the server, run:
   sudo cat /var/lib/jenkins/secrets/initialAdminPassword

Copy the password and paste it into the browse



STEP 9: COMPLETE JENKINS SETUP
  In the browser:
  Click Install suggested plugins
  Wait for plugin installation
  Create an Admin User
  Username: admin (or your choice)
  Password: strong password

Save and Finish

You will land on the Jenkins Dashboard.













































































